===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
Two forms are attested in the oracle bone script:
# {{Han compound|ls=ic|身|alt1=㐆|t1=person with a swollen belly|矢|t2=arrow-like object|又|t3=hand}} — a hand directing an arrow-like object at a person's belly. {{zh-ref|Chen (2019)}} identifies this as the original character of {{och-l|慇|abdominal pain > sorrowful; earnest}}.
# {{Han compound|ls=ic|㐆|t1=person with a swollen belly|殳|t2=hand holding a mallet}} — a hand directing a mallet at a person's belly. {{zh-ref|Chen (2019)}} associates the mallet with percussion instruments, signifying "grand music", which generalized to "grand", "substantial", "numerous", and "deep red".

In the Anhui University bamboo slips, the character is written as {{lang|zh|𫴄}} (composed of {{zh-l|*宀}}, {{zh-l|*西}}, {{zh-l|*土}}, and {{zh-l|*攴}}). This form is likely connected to the Shang ritual of burning large-bellied shamans ({{zh-l|*巫尪}}) to pray for rain, given that {{zh-l|*土}} was frequently conflated with {{zh-l|*火|fire}}, {{zh-l|*西}} with a human head, and {{zh-l|*攴}} represents a hand holding a striking implement. Furthermore, {{lang|zh|𫴄}} is structurally linked to {{lang|zh|𡫚}} (composed of {{zh-l|*宀}}, {{zh-l|*西}}, {{zh-l|*火}}, and {{zh-l|*示}}), the Zhou-dynasty script variant of {{och-l|禋|smoke sacrifice}}.

===Etymology===
Old Chinese {{och-l|殷|tr=*ʔ(ˤr)ən(ʔ)}} may be cognate with a semantic word family encompassing the following concepts{{rfv-etym|zh}}:
* to stuff, to accumulate, to block;
* to wrap, to contain, to cover;
* warmth, brewing, stability;
* deep, suppressed emotions.

